</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Co.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stay a little longer my dear Phoebe, I have no plea&s;ure but in your company, in your innocent &s;miles and endearing conver&s;ation, you have &s;carce been with me an hour, is that too much for love, when you would &s;acrifice your whole life to duty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Phoe.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh fye Colin, can you talk &s;o, hav'n't I li&s;ten|ed to you all the morning? Didn't you meet me as I came out of the wood, where I had been to carry my father's breakfa&s;t, and is it not now almo&s;t noon, for &s;ee every body is going to dinner, what do you think my mother will &s;ay.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Co.</SPEAKER>
<P>One moment more I conjure. <STAGE>[Holding her.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Phoe.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let me go Colin, you know what a noi&s;e &s;he always makes, I had a great deal of anger about the no&s;egay which you gave me, indeed &s;he rated and que&s;|tioned me all day about it, to appea&s;e her I was fain to &s;ay I had gathered it my&s;elf, but I won't tell any more &s;tories for you Colin. Let me go.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Phoe.</SPEAKER>
<L>What a &s;colding I got t'other day for the flow'r,</L>
<L>Which kneeling you forc'd me to chu&s;e;</L>
<L>Your look was &s;o tender I had not the pow'r,</L>
<L>I had not the will to refu&s;e.</L>
<L>Ah treacherous Colin,</L>
<L>Ah treacherous Colin, that ro&s;e-bud I doubt</L>
<L>A thorn in my bo&s;om has been,</L>
<L>While artful you &s;trove to adorn it without,</L>
<L>You pilfer'd, you pilfer'd, its peace from within,</L>
<L>You pilfer'd, you pilfer'd, its peace from within.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Co.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear angel Phoebe.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph$e.</SPEAKER>
<P>If my m$$her &s;hould catch us together, it will cau&s;e a great deal of mi&s;chief, as &s;he is determined I &s;hall marry Farmer Wheatear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="5" REF="5">
<SPEAKER>Co.</SPEAKER>
<P>Farmer Wheatear!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, her old friend and neighbour, who is a rich widower, and a more &s;uitable match than you, as &s;he &s;ays, as he is arrived at years of di&s;cretion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Co.</SPEAKER>
<P>What do I hear! will Phoebe for&s;ake me, I had no joy in life, but the hopes of pa&s;&s;ing it with her, and though I'd nothing but my&s;elf to offer, I fondly fancied Phoebe's heart would make me richer than a king. See how I'm di&s;tre&s;s'd, and if you have no love, be not wholly de&s;titute of compa&s;&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<L>You afflict me Colin.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Co.</SPEAKER>
<L>And you drive me to de&s;pair.</L>
<STAGE>[Noi&s;e of chopping wood.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hark! don't you hear my father at work hard by, he'll certainly di&s;cover us&mdash;Lets retire.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Co.</SPEAKER>
<P>How much I love you Phoebe.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I believe I love you&mdash;but not much, re|member.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Co.</SPEAKER>
<P>Charming maid&mdash;but the farmer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let me alone, I tell you that I will con&s;tantly refu&s;e him, and who knows what time may bring about away, away.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Co.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then on my Phoebe's love I will rely.</P>
</SP>
