<DIV2>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(rai&s;ing his voice)</STAGE>
<P>Why wi$e I &s;ay,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your wife! you have no regard for either her or your children, ar'n't you over head and ears in debt to the whole village?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(contemptuou&s;ly)</STAGE>
<P>In debt! what does that &s;ignify?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't they threaten us every day with &s;ending us to pri&s;on, and &s;han't we be oblig'd to come upon the pari&s;h for &s;upport.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>Its more likely the pari&s;h will come upon us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here's been &s;everal of your creditors this morn|ing, who &s;wear they won't wait another day, I dare &s;ay we &s;hall have them again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall be glad to &s;ee 'em.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(rai&s;ing her voice)</STAGE>
<P>But you won't be glad to hear them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not unle&s;s their voices are a little &s;ofter than yours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have no patience! will you think of providing for your daughter Phoebe, Farmer Wheatear demands her in marriage, his fortune will a&s;&s;i&s;t us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>His fortune! Pi&s;h.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>He's rich.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>Rich! Farmer Wheatear rich!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who then will you give her to?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>To the &s;quire.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="12" REF="12">
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you dream?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>To a lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Are you drunk?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>To the King.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Are you mad?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>That you'll find out by and by.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>What non&s;en&s;e!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>In a word, I am the happie&s;t of men, and if you're wi&s;e, you &s;hall be the happie&s;t of women, I have more power than the high &s;heriff, and more wealth than a nabob.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>He's certainly out of his mind.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did you &s;ee a per&s;on in boots &s;lip thro' the key hole ju&s;t now, as you came out.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly mad! no, how &s;hould I?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, li&s;ten. Standing exactly where we now are, wearied to death with my morning's work, grum|bling at our hard fate, and cur&s;ing from my &s;oul your diabolical temper.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din</SPEAKER>
<P>How traitor, have you any thing to reproach me with?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>We'll leave that &s;ubject at pre&s;ent, but as I was &s;aying all of a &s;udden, a demon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heaven forbid.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>At the noi&s;e of my complaint, came to my a&s;&s;i&s;tance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>And have you &s;old your&s;elf Booze?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no, he's only an unhappy devil like my|&s;elf, who has been plagued the&s;e ten years with a cla|morous wife, and a tumultuous &s;et of creditors, I have lent him my a&s;&s;i&s;tance to get rid of the latter, and for the re&s;t, he mu&s;t turn philo&s;opher like me, and put up with it. In recompence for this favour he a&s;&s;ured me&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>What has he a&s;&s;ured you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>That I might at my option form three wi&s;h|es&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>I could form a thou&s;and, for in&s;tance, To &s;ee you a little more rea&s;onable, one! To &s;ee you work more, two! To &s;ee you drink le&s;s, three!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="13" REF="13">
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>And that all the three &s;hould be accompli&s;hed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Accompli&s;hed! &s;eriou&s;ly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's the fact.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din</SPEAKER>
<P>Three wi&s;hes!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>And for three different things, isn't it &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>Without doubt.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ch charming! Three Wi&s;hes, delightful!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(A&s;&s;uming con&s;equence.)</STAGE>
<P>I am a drunkard, am I?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>A hang dog.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be quiet. <STAGE>(&s;topping his mouth)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>A man that don't love his wife.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>O yes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nor his children.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Will you never have done? who could tell.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, &s;hake hands Dame, good fortune makes friends of every body.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>You hav'n't begun to wi&s;h yet I hope.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, that's the difficulty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be &s;ure to take care how to proceed. Three Wi&s;hes! there are but three remember, it is not as if there were a hundred.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's true enough.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>If your dear wife now &s;hould think of &s;omething.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't be in a hurry, two heads are better than one you know, I'll go and con&s;ult with &s;quire Solemn the Ju&s;tice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Suppo&s;e you invite him to our hou&s;e, my love, then we may all con&s;ider the matter over at the &s;ame time.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will &s;o, I dare &s;ay he'll come, he's not proud in the lea&s;t, I once &s;at within two of him at the pari&s;h meeting. He doesn't indeed &s;ay much but then he's an excellent head. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<DIV3 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG. <STAGE>Booze.</STAGE></HEAD>
<LG>
<L>In grave debate they only grate,</L>
<L>Who &s;imple are and young,</L>
<L><PB N="14" REF="14">
The learn'd and wi&s;e when they advi&s;e,</L>
<L>Look big, but hold their tongue.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Thus female wit is &s;eldom fit,</L>
<L>As &s;ages oft have &s;ung;</L>
<L>Therefore in life the prudent wife,</L>
<L>Should always hold her tongue.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>What a change! it &s;eems like a dream&mdash;farewell to &s;pinning and brown bread.&mdash;No more Dame Din, but Madam Din, or my Lady&s;hip Din, I &s;hall &s;it in the great pew in the church, my hair &s;hall be dre&s;t, and powder'd, and &s;tand bolt up on an end, with a band round it like a wheat&s;heaf&mdash;I'll look under my eyes, &s;o, at my neighbours&mdash;I'll dine at midnight, and get up in the afternoon&mdash;Lord what a life will that be.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Farmer Wheatear.</STAGE>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>DUETT.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<L>Adieu to the village,</L>
<L>To toil and to tillage</L>
<L>Squire Booze and his Lady,</L>
<L>Squire Booze and his Lady,</L>
</SP>
<SP>
