<L>Lord what can &s;he ail.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<L>In a coach I'll be drawn,</L>
<L>In a coach I'll be drawn,</L>
<L>There I'll loll and I'll Yawn,</L>
<L>I'll yawn.</L>
<L><PB N="15" REF="15">
Its Grand to be lazy</L>
<L>Its grand</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<L>She's certainly crazy</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<L>Then I and my daughter</L>
<L>I'm bur&s;ting with laughter,</L>
<L>Then I and my daughter,</L>
<L>We'll live like the ladies, the ladies in tow$</L>
<L>Our friends and relations and relations un|known.</L>
<L>Ha, ha, ha&punc; ha, ha!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<L>Ha, ha, ha, ha, ha!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<L>Ha, ha, ha, ha&punc; ha!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<L>Ha, hu, hu, hu, hu!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<L>O what delight</L>
<L>To be mix'd every night,</L>
<L>With lords and fine folks,</L>
<L>To dance and cut jokes</L>
<L>Dance, &amp;c.</L>
<L>My lord I'm your &s;ervant,</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<L>Ha&punc; ha, ha, ha, ha!</L>
<L>My lady, I'm your &s;ervant.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't let me di&s;compo&s;e you Dame, you &s;eem very well &s;atisfied with your&s;elf to day&mdash;may one a&s;k the rea&s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Its not without rea&s;on I a&s;&s;ure you&mdash;but per|haps I won't open my mouth for a twelve month.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not open your mouth for a twelve month, that would be a wonder indeed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>You think &s;o Farmer, do you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye that I do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(to her&s;elf)</STAGE>
<P>The whole village will bur&s;t with envy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dame Din.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Without hearing him.)</STAGE>
<P>Yes the whole village.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>It &s;eems to have taken away your hearing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ay my wedding with Phoebe mu&s;t &s;hortly take place.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your wedding with Phoebe! Farmer Wheat|ear's wedding with Phoebe! ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="6" REF="16">
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha! I can contain no longer&mdash;did not you give me&punc;your promi&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have &s;ome faint remembrance of it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>But not to di&s;plea&s;e you Dame, you take upon your&s;elf a great deal, ye&s;terday you thought me a good match for your daughter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>True, ye&s;terday Farmer Wheatear's offer was ac|ceptable, but this is another day and all days are not a|like.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>How, are not you the &s;ame you was ye&s;terday; Dame Din&punc; wife of Booze, a poor labouring man; and am not I Farmer Wheatear, the riche&s;t farmer in the pari&s;h.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes you are, and always will be the rich Farm|er Wheatear, but I &s;hall not be Dame Din much longer, nor will Phoebe be the daughter of Booze the poor la|bouring man. <STAGE>[Exit curt&s;ying.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat</SPEAKER>
<P>She raves, &s;he's out of her mind, but I'll go &s;eek her hu&s;band if he &s;hould luckily happen to be &s;ober, I may chance to get it explained. Did not my regard to Phoebe force me to per&s;i&s;t, I would leave this extra|ordinary couple entirely to them&s;elves.</P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
