<DIV2>
<HEAD>ACT II.</HEAD>
<STAGE>SCENE The Country, COLIN, PHOEBE, <HI>Dame</HI> DIN, <HI>and Farmer</HI> WHEATEAR in their be&s;t Cloaths.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PHOEBE.</SPEAKER>
<P>IS it true mother, that we are going to be &s;o va&s;tly rich&mdash;my father told me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold your tongue, chit, the&s;e are not mat|ters
<PB N="18" REF="18">
for you to pry into, however you mu&s;t think no more of Farmer Wheatear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>But neighbour</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>But neighbour&mdash;Will you obey Phoebe?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly mother.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>There's a good child, but you &s;hould call me mama, now come and ki&s;s me, Phoebe &s;ince you're &s;o tractable, but hold up your head and look jauntly, I have got a hu&s;band for you that you'll like a thou&s;and times better.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear mama, how much I am obliged to you, Colin is indeed the mo&s;t amiable.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Diu.</SPEAKER>
<P>How Colin&mdash;What Colin?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why don't you ki&s;s her, when &s;he's &s;o tractable.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>So, &s;o, now I di&s;cover the hi&s;tory of the no&s;e|gay, and the rea&s;on why you are &s;o long in coming from the wood, but no matter, you mu&s;t give up this mo&s;t amiable Colin immediately.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! be not &s;o unkind!</P>
</SP>
<DIV3 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG. <HI>Phoebe.</HI></HEAD>
<LG>
<L>As yet in the morn of my youth,</L>
<L>A parent's advice I revere,</L>
<L>A parent's, &amp;c.</L>
<L>But oh while you cheri&s;h my truth,</L>
<L>Think my happine&s;s equally dear,</L>
<L>Think, &amp;c.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>My pa&s;&s;ion's not founded on time,</L>
<L>Young Colin fir&s;t taught it to glow,</L>
<L>And the brea&s;t which hath kindled for him,</L>
<L>No warmth for another can know.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Sincere and re&s;pectful to you,</L>
<L>To Colin as con&s;tant I'll prove,</L>
<L>For the heart that to duty is true,</L>
<L>Will always be faithful to love.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>And you are determin'd to think of Colin, per|ver&s;e minx, are you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is impo&s;&s;ible to help thinking of him, I can never forget Colin while I live.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="19" REF="19">
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>You impudent hu&s;&s;ey, that <STAGE>[Going to &s;trike her,</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Soft, &s;oft, Dame <STAGE>(receives the blow)</STAGE> the devil's in the woman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now I fancy yon'll obey me madam Pert, but I forgot the great affair all this time, while I am loite|ring here, my hu&s;band may commit &s;ome folly, its ne|ce&s;&s;ary I &s;hould always be at his elbow.</P>
</SP>
<DIV3 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG. <STAGE>Din.</STAGE></HEAD>
<LG>
<L>Not &s;o certain we know,</L>
<L>As a word and a blow,</L>
<L>To regulate matters dome&s;tic</L>
<L>To manage the hou&s;e,</L>
<L>To qualify the &s;pou&s;e,</L>
<L>They conquer who brandi&s;h the be&s;t &s;tick,</L>
<L>They conquer, &amp;c.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>She that's quiet and cool,</L>
<L>Poor good-natur'd fool,</L>
<L>What mortal will find out her merit,</L>
<L>In each &s;tation of life,</L>
<L>For maid, widow or wife,</L>
<L>There's nought like a woman of &s;pirit. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm quite concerned Farmer Wheatear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>For what my lovely girl.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<P>For the box which you received on my account.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never mind it Phoebe, my cheek is more a|ble to bear it than this &s;oft one. <STAGE>[Patting her cheek.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<P>My mother has a heavy hand.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Rather &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope it did not hurt you much.</P>
<STAGE>[Putting her hand to his face</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Ki&s;&s;ing her hand.)</STAGE>
<P>Now all the pain is fled&punc; and if you would but think of me for a hu&s;band.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<P>Think of you for a hu&s;band, Mr Wheatear, that's impo&s;&s;ible.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why my little dear, with me you &s;hall enjoy all the plea&s;ures of life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alas Farmer, I am very young, and unexperi|enced,
<PB N="20" REF="20">
but I thought all the plea&s;ures of life cannot be en|joyed till the heart is at ea&s;e&mdash;Colin's company, his love and his e&s;teem are all that I de&s;ire.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE>
<P>Poor girl, I pity her, her mother has refu&s;ed me, the daughter is in love with another, I am no longer young, can I blame her, why then &s;hould I per&s;i&s;t in making her wretched?&mdash;Phoebe</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<P>What &s;ay you Farmer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>So you are determined to mary no other but Colin.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<P>That I never will.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I am determined <STAGE>[Aff$cting anger.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<P>To do what!&mdash;I hope you won't di&s;tre&s;s me more.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>To go this moment to your father and en|deavour to get his con&s;ent for you&mdash;to marry Colin.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Farmer how &s;hall I thank you.</P>
<STAGE>[Jumping on his neck.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE>Colin <HI>entering.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ah Colin.</SPEAKER>
<P>come hither Colin.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Co.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;eem too well engaged already.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope to be better engaged by and by.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Co.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why by and by, Phoebe, ar'n't you &s;ufficiently entertained at pre&s;ent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>He's jealous, but I'll not torment him, poor lad don't be unea&s;y, that embrace was all for love of you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Co.</SPEAKER>
<P>Its a &s;trange way of &s;howing it, I never received &s;uch a proof before.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fye Colin, but you mu&s;t embrace him your&s;elf, and thank him too, he's going to &s;peak to my father for us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Co.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can I believe it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>You may, and though there won't be &s;o much between you, there'll be more love, and that's the be&s;t &s;tock to &s;et up with.</P>
</SP>
<DIV3 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG. <STAGE>Wheatear.</STAGE></HEAD>
<LG>
<L>Then away to papa,</L>
<L>Where we'll but &s;cold mma,</L>
<L><PB N="21" REF="21">
And a wedding 'twill be without pelf,</L>
<L>Then away to papa, &amp;c.</L>
<L>We'll have a &s;ack po&s;&s;et,</L>
<L>That nothing may cro&s;s it;</L>
<L>And I'll throw the &s;tocking my&s;elf, my&s;elf,</L>
<L>Fall&punc; lall, lall, lall, lall de rall, lall, lall,</L>
</LG>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Chorus.</SPEAKER>
<L>Fall, lall, lall, de rall, lall, lall. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></L>
</SP>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<STAGE>SCENE, A Table ready for Pudding to come up at the Wi&s;h.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BOOZE.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have &s;een nothing of my friend Belphegor, where the devil can $e have hid him&s;elf all this time; Perhaps he has left us for a warmer climate, but then he promi|&s;ed to appear in ca&s;e I wanted his advice&mdash;His Wor&s;hip the Ju&s;tice however, will make that needle&s;s; what a &s;ine thing it is to be rich, or to have it in one's power to be &s;o, &s;ince my adventure has been known in the vil|lage, the quarrel has been who &s;hould oblige me mo&s;t, my creditors have lo&s;t their memories, and forgot that I ever owed them a farthing&mdash;Every body is my be&s;t friend, walk in Mr Booze, come and take pot-luck with us neighbour, continually offering me all their fortune, in hopes of partaking mine, ble&s;s me, what a number of favours a per&s;on receives when he has no occa&s;ion for any.</P>
</SP>
<DIV3 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG. <STAGE>Booze.</STAGE></HEAD>
<LG>
<L>They court, they care&s;s me,</L>
<L>They cringe, they addre&s;s me;</L>
<L>Good-morrow friend, good-morrow,</L>
<L>Good-morrow.</L>
<L>I hope your hearty, why &s;o dull,</L>
<L>Can I a&s;&s;i&s;t, my pur&s;e is full,</L>
<L>Perchance you want to borrow,</L>
<L>Perchance, &amp;c.</L>
<L>Tho' virtue when &s;tarving,</L>
<L>Is &s;carce worth pre&s;erving;</L>
<L><PB N="22" REF="22">
When once the pocket's heavy,</L>
<L>When, &amp;c.</L>
<L>Tho' &s;tain'd in guilt, and &s;unk in vice,</L>
<L>But ope the door and in a trice,</L>
<L>You'll have a crouded levce,</L>
<L>You'll have, &amp;c.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Solemn.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your &s;ervant friend, your &s;ervant, I am glad to &s;ee you, I am glad to hear&mdash;But I &s;ay nothing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank your Wor&s;hip&mdash;I expected you wou'd come, this is a very weighty affair I have upon my hands.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know&mdash;I know&mdash;But I &s;ay nothing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank your Wor&s;hip, I &s;hall have need of all your advice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;hall be a&s;&s;i&s;ted, be not di&s;turbed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, but I am very much di&s;turbed, I don't wonder that the riche&s;t people are not the mo&s;t happy, the bare expectation of it, &s;ets me be&s;ide my&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't be di&s;turbed I &s;ay, to give advice is my fort, and all the world think them&s;elves advantaged by it, for this rea&s;on, becau&s;e my advice is excellent&mdash;But I &s;ay nothing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>So much the better.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>No Lawyer, Barri&s;ter, Special Pleader or Whip|per Snapper Attorney, dare before me&mdash;But I &s;ay nothing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>So much the better.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am no having Ju&s;tice, no mercenary, I take no brief, but then my advice is brief&mdash;I &s;ay nothing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>So much the better, &s;o much the better,&mdash;Will your Wor&s;hip take a chair. <STAGE><HI>(Enter</HI> Wheatear)</STAGE> Good-day neighbours, come, and welcome his Wor|&s;hip.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>With all my heart, and I'm heartily glad to meet you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well Farmer, do you &s;till love Phoebe.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, but I have di&s;covered &s;omebody el&s;e
<PB N="23" REF="23">
who loves her too&mdash;in a word neighbour, young Colin is the per&s;on &s;uited to your daughter, their years, their inclinations agree, from the fir&s;t of life, he has cultiva|ted her good opinion, and now it has ripen'd into love. He ought to reap the harve&s;t of his labour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>What wou'd your wor&s;hip advi&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ay nothing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed neighbour you mu&s;t con&s;ent to their happine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>At pre&s;ent I'm engaged with his Wor&s;hip, on bu&s;ine&s;s of con&s;equence, nothing of that &s;ort can be &s;ettled to-day, can it Mr Ju&s;tice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>And pray Farmer give us your company.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why neighbour, they &s;ay you are going to be a great man&mdash;How is this?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>The very thing I wanted to communicate to you, it depends upon my&s;elf&mdash;The Ju&s;tice and I, are now preparing to con&s;ult about it&mdash;You will not be one too many.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then it mu&s;t be a trea&s;ure.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mu&s;t it think you, mu&s;t I wi&s;h for a trea&s;ure&mdash;That would be no bad thing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>There is no occa&s;ion to wi&s;h for what you have already.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have not got it yet.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your wife a&s;&s;ured me you had.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>My wife's a fool.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>I thought as much.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Din.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>My &s;tars are you here old&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>And why not, the Farmer is a man of under|&s;tanding&mdash;He will a&s;&s;i&s;t us&mdash;Be&s;ides his Wor&s;hip has been beating his brains this hour without producing any thing, and you know&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Getting up from his chair.)</STAGE>
<P>Moderation my friend&mdash;Moderation, three wi&s;hes you &s;ay&mdash;But I &s;ay nothing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="24" REF="24">
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>What do you mean by three Wi&s;hes, is that the trea&s;ure?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll explain it all to you. <STAGE><HI>[To</HI> Wheatear.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(to the <HI>Ju&s;tice)</HI></STAGE>
<P>I rejoice to &s;ee your honour in our little cottage&mdash;but what will it be by and by.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know&mdash;But I &s;ay nothing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope your honour won't think of li&s;tening to my hu&s;band&mdash;who between you and me, is no wi&s;er than he &s;hould be&mdash;I am but a woman, and his wife, but mark me, I have more &s;en&s;e in my little &s;inger.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>What &s;pirit! but affairs of this kind require very wi&s;e heads indeed&mdash;But I &s;ay nothing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>The devil it does Mr Booze.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well Mr Ju&s;tice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't interrupt me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>I long to &s;ee the end of this bu&s;ine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>Suppo&s;e we &s;it down at the table&mdash;Your Wor|&s;hip will perhaps find it ea&s;ier for &s;tudying.&mdash;Wife get us &s;ome Ale.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>A Lucky thought.&mdash;Good bright Ale, bright|ens the wit.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sometimes it does and &s;ometimes it does not, on the contrary there are in&s;tances&mdash;and they depend upon circum&s;tances in hopes&mdash;But I &s;ay nothing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's right, now &s;it down.</P>
<STAGE>[To his wife who is coming with the Ale.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Room, room for my Lady.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>The nearer I approach the grand moment the more I am di&s;quieted.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Like enough&mdash;like enough.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let's drink and keep up our &s;pirits.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Moderation, gentlemen, moderation.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Takes the tankard from him and takes a long draught.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>I think you have rather too much Mr Ju&s;tice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Wi&s;h Booze.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now we are come to it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>In the fir&s;t place your Cellar to be always well &s;tored.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="25" REF="25">
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's nothing at all.&mdash;Your Wife to be always hand&s;ome.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;ha I want fortune&mdash;and a hand&s;ome wife is of more u&s;e to the gallant than the hu&s;band&mdash;don't you think &s;o Mr Ju&s;tice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ay nothing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>But if your Wor&s;hip &s;till continues &s;aying no|thing we &s;hall never come to the end of our bu&s;ine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>We are not nearer now than we were at the be|ginning.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let's employ the tankard perhaps we &s;hall find it at the bottom.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>Drink as much as you plea&s;e if that will do, but we ought to have &s;omething to eat at the &s;ame time $word$ &s;ee what there is in the pantry.&mdash;I am told your $word$ loves a hunting Pudding, we had an excellent one la&s;t Sunday&mdash;I wi&s;h with all my heart we had &s;uch another now. <STAGE>[Pudding appears upon table.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>A Pudding! <STAGE>[&s;tarting.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Good &s;oul.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Moderation I tell you.&mdash;I never ta&s;ted a nicer di&s;h in all my life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I fancy our landlord thinks it a dear one.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have been to blame, I own it, but we have two wi&s;hes remaining.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Two devils.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>True, and I can't tell which torments me mo&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>If you &s;cold all day it won't mend the matter. <STAGE>[His mouth full.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes dunderhead, when you might have had a kingdom full of gold, you wi&s;h'd for a pudding&mdash;go&mdash;&s;hall indeed&mdash;I won't &s;ay what.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's right don't &s;ay what.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>If I had been to have wi&s;h'd&mdash;You &s;hou'd have &s;een&mdash;You &s;hou'd have &s;een.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(in a pa&s;&s;ion)</STAGE>
<P>Hold your tongue, railing, &s;colding, vixen, hold your tongue&mdash;I wi&s;h you'd lo&s;t the u&s;e of it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="26" REF="26">
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Two wi&s;hes di&s;po&s;ed of ha, ha, ha!</P>
<STAGE>[Exit Dame <HI>Din.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>This it is not to have moderation, and as this is the ca&s;e, I have no further bu&s;ine&s;s here, neverthele&s;s Mr Booze for the pre&s;ent, I would advi&s;e you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze</SPEAKER>
<P>To hang my&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, that's an affair of Ju&s;tice&mdash;And &s;entence is never pronounced but in Court.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze</SPEAKER>
<P>Two wi&s;hes thrown away.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>But your wife neighbour&punc; won't &s;tun you with her melody any longer, that's &s;omething gain'd however.</P>
</SP>
<DIV3 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG. <STAGE>Wheatear.</STAGE></HEAD>
<LG>
<L>Cheer up my friends your cares defy,</L>
<L>Your comforts now are budding.</L>
<L>What hu&s;band would not gladly buy</L>
<L>His quiet for a Pudding.</L>
<L>His quiet &amp;c.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>The winter checks the ri&s;ing crop,</L>
<L>The &s;pring we know is warmer,</L>
<L>For brighter hours we live and hope,</L>
<L>So &s;ays the country farmer.</L>
<L>So &s;ays &amp;c.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>What matters now &s;ince madam's dumb,</L>
<L>If hence &s;he wear the breeches,</L>
<L>From wife that's mute no ill can come,</L>
<L>Then bear your lo&s;s of riches.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>No &s;orrow let your looks betray,</L>
<L>In mirth the &s;ure&s;t truth is,</L>
<L>Swallow your griefs and nothing &s;ay,</L>
<L>So thinks the country Ju&s;tice.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<STAGE>(Thunder, Clock &s;trikes, <HI>Belphegor</HI> comes from the ca&s;e.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be not terrified my friends, my hone&s;t landlord knew I was his gue&s;t though concealed&mdash;I promi&s;ed to appear when mo&s;t he wanted my advice, and notwith|&s;tanding his learned friend's a&s;&s;i&s;tance, I fear he has much occa&s;ion for it now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="27" REF="27">
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>What blu&s;tering gentleman is this, I am afraid he'll bring the hou&s;e about our ears.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bel.</SPEAKER>
<P>What's that you &s;ay &s;ir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ay nothing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is his infernal Wor&s;hip&mdash;by who&s;e kind|ne&s;s, added to your wi&s;e coun&s;el, I have gained many advantages&mdash;Will you be introduced to him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>By no means, a magi&s;trate &s;hould not be &s;een in &s;uch company.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bel.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am truly concerned that my gratitude for the kindne&s;s you &s;howed me, &s;hould have turned out &s;o lit|tle to your advantage&mdash;I am now &s;ummoned away, and all my wordly cares are over, anxious however for your welfare, the few moments allowed me &s;hall be &s;pent in endeavouring to promote it, &s;eek no more to aggrandize yo$r&s;elf, nor wi&s;h for fancied plea&s;ures, real peace; let your third wi&s;h be given to recover your dome&s;tic felici|ty, without which, know from experience, there can be no happine&s;s in life: Re&s;tore your wife to her &s;peech, live temperate, be frugal and indu&s;trious, and you will probably enjoy more ea&s;e and comfort, than in the gra|tification of the mo&s;t unbounded de&s;ires.</P>
</SP>
<LG>
<L>Then learn to prize your humble lot,</L>
<L>Improve the little you have got,</L>
<L>And when content appears in view,</L>
<L>You'll own the devil told you true. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></L>
</LG>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm glad he's gone, notwith&s;tanding the kind lecture he gave us&mdash;I've been in a devili&s;h fright ever &s;ince he appeared.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Colin <HI>and</HI> Phoebe.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Co.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(To Wheatear.)</STAGE>
<P>Have they at la&s;t con&s;ented.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here comes madam Din, &s;he'll tell you if &s;he's able.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Din.</HI> She makes &s;igns of penitence.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>All the&s;e &s;igns will do no good.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear papa, have pity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="28" REF="28">
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>Only one wi&s;h more, come let's be a King at once, wife &s;hould you like to become a Queen.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>What a Queen, and not talk no, no <HI>(Din &s;hakes her head)</HI> I thought &s;o, come, come, you mu&s;t forgive her, and do as your friend Lucifer advi&s;ed you, for after all, I believe that will be the be&s;t way.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze</SPEAKER>
<P>Well I wi&s;h&mdash;I wi&s;h&mdash;That my wife may re|cover the u&s;e of her tongue <STAGE>[Fetches a deep &s;igh.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah my dear friend&mdash;My good hu&s;band&mdash;My kind man, embrace me again&mdash;And you Farmer&mdash;And you Colin&mdash;And you Phaebe&mdash;And all of you, I con|&s;ent to every thing, I oppo&s;e nothing&mdash;You have all a&s;|&s;i&s;ted me&mdash;Give me your hand Booze, and your's my children love each other&mdash;I have forbid you, but now I recommend it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>What a torrent!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>It will be our turn by and by.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ph.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear mama, I am rejoiced.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Din.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stop, let me &s;peak&mdash;What was I &s;aying, I for|get where I left off.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then you had better begin again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>S'Blood we've had enough.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat,</SPEAKER>
<P>ha, ha, ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>This laughing won't pay my debts&mdash;If I was but clear in the world, I &s;hou'd not care a fig for any thing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wheat.</SPEAKER>
<P>Give me your hand, I'll take care to &s;ettle your demands&mdash;for tho' I'm not to be your relation, you &s;hall always find me your friend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Booze.</SPEAKER>
<P>If &s;o, come and ki&s;s me Dame, and now you may talk as fa&s;t as you plea&s;e. Henceforth I will follow Belphegor's advice, and look for happine&s;s in my own little family, by my own cheerful fire&s;ide. What &s;ay you Mr Ju&s;tice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ay nothing.</P>
</SP>
